            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is the Arrhenius equation?</h2>
              <p>
                The Arrhenius equation describes how the rate constant \(k\) of
                a chemical reaction depends on temperature:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( k = A \, e^{-E_a / (R T)} \)</div>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(k\)</strong> – rate constant (units depend on
                  reaction order)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(A\)</strong> – pre-exponential (frequency) factor,
                  same units as \(k\)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(E_a\)</strong> – activation energy (J·mol⁻¹ or
                  kJ·mol⁻¹)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(R\)</strong> – gas constant, typically \(8.314\
                  \text{J·mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(T\)</strong> – absolute temperature in kelvin (K)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Physically, \(E_a\) represents the energy barrier that reactant
                molecules must overcome to form products. As temperature
                increases, more molecules have enough energy to cross this
                barrier, so the reaction speeds up.
              </p>

              <h2>Rearranged forms of the Arrhenius equation</h2>
              <h3>Solving for the rate constant \(k\)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">\( k = A \, e^{-E_a / (R T)} \)</div>
              <p>
                This is the most common use: given \(A\), \(E_a\), and \(T\),
                compute the rate constant.
              </p>

              <h3>Solving for activation energy \(E_a\)</h3>
              <p>From a single data point:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( E_a = - R T \ln\left(\dfrac{k}{A}\right) \)
              </div>
              <p>From two rate constants at different temperatures:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \ln\left(\dfrac{k_2}{k_1}\right) =
                -\dfrac{E_a}{R}\left(\dfrac{1}{T_2} - \dfrac{1}{T_1}\right) \)
                <br /><br />
                \( E_a = -\,\dfrac{R \, \ln(k_2/k_1)}{(1/T_2 - 1/T_1)} \)
              </div>

              <h3>Solving for temperature \(T\)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( T = \dfrac{E_a}{R \, \ln(A/k)} \)
              </div>
              <p>
                This tells you what temperature is required to reach a desired
                rate constant, assuming \(A\) and \(E_a\) remain constant.
              </p>

              <h2>Arrhenius plots: ln(k) vs 1/T</h2>
              <p>
                Taking the natural logarithm of the Arrhenius equation gives a
                linear form:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \ln k = \ln A - \dfrac{E_a}{R}\dfrac{1}{T} \)
              </div>
              <p>
                If you plot \(\ln k\) (y-axis) against \(1/T\) (x-axis), you
                should obtain a straight line with:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>slope</strong> \(m = -E_a/R\)</li>
                <li><strong>intercept</strong> \(b = \ln A\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>From the slope, you can estimate the activation energy:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( E_a = -m R \)</div>

              <h2>Worked example: rate constant at a higher temperature</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose a reaction has \(E_a = 50\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}\) and \(A
                = 1.0 \times 10^{12}\ \text{s}^{-1}\). What is \(k\) at
                \(25^\circ\text{C}\) (298 K)?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert \(E_a\) to J·mol⁻¹: \(50\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1} = 5.0
                  \times 10^4\ \text{J·mol}^{-1}\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use \(R = 8.314\ \text{J·mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\) and \(T =
                  298\ \text{K}\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute the exponent: \[ -\dfrac{E_a}{R T} =
                  -\dfrac{5.0\times10^4}{8.314 \times 298} \approx -20.2 \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute \(k\): \[ k = 1.0\times10^{12} \times e^{-20.2}
                  \approx 1.7\times10^3\ \text{s}^{-1} \]
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                You can reproduce this calculation in the single-temperature
                mode by entering \(A\), \(E_a\), and \(T\), and solving for
                \(k\).
              </p>

              <h2>Common pitfalls and best practices</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Always use absolute temperature (K)</strong> in the
                  Arrhenius equation. The calculator converts from °C to K for
                  you.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Keep energy units consistent</strong> with the gas
                  constant. This tool internally converts kJ·mol⁻¹ and
                  kcal·mol⁻¹ to J·mol⁻¹.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Beware of mechanism changes</strong>: if the reaction
                  mechanism changes with temperature, a single Arrhenius fit may
                  not describe all data.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use multiple data points</strong> and an Arrhenius
                  plot when possible; it gives a more reliable estimate of
                  \(E_a\) than just two temperatures.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

